anfaes, Anglesey, Wales","Abey, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Bradwell-on-Sea, Essex, England":"Bradwell-on-Sea, Essex, Anglie","John, Saint-Laurent-du-Maroni, French Guiana":"John, Francouzská Guyana"},"da":{"1180–2 February 1237":"1180–2. februar 1237","1180–1237":"1180–1237","1180–1241":"1180–1241","1210–1284":"1210–1284","1160–Male":"1160–Afdød","1158–Female":"1158–Afdød","1237":"1237","1158":"1158","1210":"1210","2 February 1237":"2. februar 1237","1241":"1241","1284":"1284","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Llanfaes, Isle of Anglesey, Wales":"Llanfaes, Anglesey, Wales","Abey, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Bradwell-on-Sea, Essex, England":"Bradwell-on-Sea, Essex, England","John, Saint-Laurent-du-Maroni, French Guiana":"John, Fransk Guyana"},"nl":{"1180–2 February 1237":"1180–2 februari 1237","1180–1237":"1180–1237","1180–1241":"1180–1241","1210–1284":"1210–1284","1160–Male":"1160–Overleden","1158–Female":"1158–Overleden","1237":"1237","1158":"1158","1210":"1210","2 February 1237":"2 februari 1237","1241":"1241","1284":"1284","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Llanfaes, Isle of Anglesey, Wales":"Llanfaes, Anglesey, Wales","Abey, Wales":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bradwell-on-Sea, Essex, England":"Bradwell-on-Sea, Essex, England","John, Saint-Laurent-du-Maroni, French Guiana":"John, Frans-Guyana"},"en":{"1180–2 February 1237":"1180–2 February 1237","1180–1237":"1180–1237","1180–1241":"1180–1241","1210–1284":"1210–1284","1160–Male":"1160–Deceased","1158–Female":"1158–Deceased","1237":"1237","1158":"1158","1210":"1210","2 February 1237":"2 February 1237","1241":"1241","1284":"1284","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Llanfaes, Isle of Anglesey, Wales":"Llanfaes, Anglesey, Wales","Abey, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Bradwell-on-Sea, Essex, England":"Bradwell-on-Sea, Essex, England","John, Saint-Laurent-du-Maroni, French Guiana":"John, French Guiana","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan was born in 1180, in John, French Guiana, her father, Robert D'Aubigny, was 20 and her mother, Joan Bedfordshire, was 22. She had at least 1 daughter with Roger de Akeni. She died on 2 February 1237, in Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 57, and was buried in Llanfaes, Anglesey, Wales."},"et":{"1180–2 February 1237":"1180–2. veebruar 1237","1180–1237":"1180–1237","1180–1241":"1180–1241","1210–1284":"1210–1284","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1158–Female":"1158–Surnud","12